s. Today's potent televisual forms were furthermore developed in and strongly influenced by newsreels, and much of the archived newsreel footage is repeatedly used to both illustrate and re-stage past events and their significance.This book addresses newsreel cinema and television as a medium serving the formation of cultural identities in a variety of national contexts after 1945, its role in forming audiovisual narratives of a »biopic of the nation«, and the technical, aesthetical, and political challenges of archiving and restaging cinematic and televisual newsreel.  afunded by Knowledge Unlatched - KU Select 2017: Backlist Collection  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aDocumentary filmsxHistory and criticismvCongresses. 0aDocumentary television programsxHistory and criticismvCongresses. 0aGroup identityxHistoryvCongresses. 0aMotion picture journalismzGermanyxHistoryvCongresses. 0aMotion picture journalismzSwitzerlandxHistoryvCongresses. 0aMotion picture theaters. 0aNational characteristics in motion picturesvCongresses. 0aNewsreelszGermanyxHistoryvCongresses. 0aNewsreelszSwitzerlandxHistoryvCongresses. 0aTelevisionxSocial aspectsvCongresses. 4aArchive. 4aContemporary Art. 4aCultural History. 4aCultural Identity. 4aFilm. 4aMedia History. 4aMedia Studies. 4aMedia. 4aNational Identity. 4aTelevision. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  aArchive.  aContemporary Art.  aCultural History.  aCultural Identity.  aFilm.  aMedia History.  aMedia Studies.  aMedia.  aNational Identity.  aTelevision.1 aBleuler, Marcel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc